nt\n|-\n| GC ||  [[New Territories East (constituency)|New Territories East]] || {{sort|Cheung|[[Fernando Cheung]]}}|| {{Party name with color|Labour Party (Hong Kong)}} || style=\"background:#ffdd88;\"| {{n}} No\n|-\n| GC ||  [[Hong Kong Island (constituency)|Hong Kong Island]] || {{sort|Sin|[[Sin Chung-kai]]}}|| {{Party name with color|Democratic Party (Hong Kong)}} || style=\"background:#ffdd88;\"| {{n}} No\n|-\n| GC ||  [[Kowloon West (constituency)|Kowloon West]] || {{sort|Wong|[[Helena Wong (politician)|Helena Wong]]}}|| {{Party name with color|Democratic Party (Hong Kong)}} || style=\"background:#ffdd88;\"| {{n}} No\n|-\n| FC ||  [[Education (constituency)|Education]] || {{sort|Ip|[[Ip Kin-yuen]]}}|| {{Party name with color|Independent (politician)}} || style=\"background:#ffdd88;\"| {{n}} No\n|-\n| GC ||  [[New Territories East (constituency)|New Territories East]] || {{sort|Quat|[[Elizabeth Quat]]}}|| {{Party name with color|Democratic Alliance for the Betterment and Progress of Hong Kong}} || bgcolor=cacaca|Absent\n|-\n| FC ||  [[Commercial (Second)]] || {{sort|Liu|[[Martin Liao]]}}|| {{Party name with color|Independent (politician)}} || bgcolor=cacaca|Absent\n|-\n| FC ||  [[Labour (constituency)|Labour]] ||{{sort|Poon|[[Poon Siu-ping]]}}|| {{Party name with color|Federation of Hong Kong and Kowloon Labour Unions}} || bgcolor=cacaca|Absent {{ref label|poon|b}}\n|-\n| FC ||  [[Labour (constituency)|Labour]] ||{{sort|Tang|[[Tang Ka-piu]]}}|| {{Party name with color|Hong Kong Federation of Trade Unions}} || bgcolor=cacaca|Absent\n|-\n| GC ||  [[Kowloon West (constituency)|Kowloon West]] || {{sort|Chiang|[[Chiang Lai-wan]]}}|| {{Party name with color|Democratic Alliance for the Betterment and Progress of Hong Kong}} || bgcolor=cacaca|Absent\n|-\n| FC ||  [[Engineering (constituency)|Engineering]] ||{{sort|Lo|[[Lo Wai-kwok]]}}|| {{Party name with color|Business and Professionals Alliance for Hong Kong}} || bgcolor=cacaca|Absent\n|-\n| FC ||  [[Textiles and Garment (constituency)|Textiles and Garment]] ||{{sort|Chung|[[Chung Kwok-pan]]}}|| {{Party name with color|Liberal Party (Hong Kong)}} || {{y}} Yes\n|-\n| GC ||  [[Hong Kong Island (constituency)|Hong Kong Island]] || {{sort|Chung|[[Christopher Chung]]}}|| {{Party name with color|Democratic Alliance for the Betterment and Progress of Hong Kong}} || bgcolor=cacaca|Absent\n|-\n| FC ||  [[Architectural, Surveying and Planning (constituency)|Architectural, Surveying and Planning]] || {{sort|Tse|[[Tony Tse]]}}|| {{Party name with color|Independent (politician)}} || bgcolor=cacaca|Absent\n|-\n!colspan=6 style=\"text-align:left\"| Source:<ref name=\"CEVote\">{{cite web|url=http://www.legco.gov.hk/pivote/pivote.pdf|title=Council Meeting (Voting Results) 18 June 2015|publisher=Legislative Council of Hong Kong}}</ref>\n----\n{{nobold|<small>\na{{note|president}} As [[President of the Legislative Council of Hong Kong|President of the Legislative Council]], Tsang did not vote per custom. <br />\nb{{note|poon}} Poon was physically inside the chamber but did not indicate his presence and thus did not register his presence in records.\n</small>}}\n|}\n\n==International responses==\n\n===United States===\nIn April 2014, [[Anson Chan]], former [[Chief Secretary of Hong Kong]] and founder of pro-democracy group [[Hong Kong 2020]], and [[Martin Lee]], founder of Hong Kong's opposition [[Democratic Party (Hong Kong)|Democratic Party]], went to the United States and met [[Joe Biden]], US Vice-President at the [[White House]]. The activists spoke out against Beijing increasing control over Hong Kong and their fear of only candidates picked by Beijing would be allowed to take part in the 2017 Chief Executive election. Lee and Chan also voiced concerns over press freedom in Hong Kong, referring to violent assaults on journalists and alleging that Beijing is pressuring advertisers to shun critical media. Biden underscored Washington's \"long-standing support for democracy in Hong Kong and for the city's high degree of autonomy under the 'one country, two systems' framework,\" the White House said. China warned the United States against meddling in Hong Kong's internal affairs after Biden met with Chan and Lee. In response, [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs of the People's Republic of China|Chinese Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] said that it \"firmly opposes any countries meddling in the city's internal affairs in any way,\" ''[[South China Morning Post]]'' quoted.<ref name=\"Biden\">{{cite news|url=http://rt.com/news/china-us-biden-interfere-897/|title=China tells US not to meddle in Hong Kong's internal affairs|publisher=RT|date=7 April 2014}}</ref>\n\nDuring their trip to America, Lee and Chan also met with [[Nancy Pelosi]], minority leader of the [[US House of Representatives|House of Representatives]], and members of the [[Congressional-Executive Commission on China]]. \"The future of freedom and democracy in Hong Kong is under serious threat,\" Senator [[Sherrod Brown]], head of the commission, said in a prepared statement, as quoted by Reuters. \"China is already placing 'pre-conditions' on who can run, raising serious doubts about whether the elections will be free and fair,\" he added.<ref name=\"Biden\"/>\n\nIn early May 2015, A US bipartisan delegation led by [[Matt Salmon]], a [[Republican Party (US)|Republican]] who chairs the [[United States Senate Foreign Relations Subcommittee on East Asia, The Pacific and International Cybersecurity Policy|Subcommittee on East Asian and Pacific Affairs]] with Republican [[Tom Emmer]] and [[Democratic Party (US)|Democrat]] [[Alan Lowenthal]] on a fact-finding mission visited Hong Kong to learn about developments in Hong Kong. They held meetings with Chief Executive Leung Chun-ying and also legislators across the spectrum on the government's reform package, which pan-democrats have pledged to reject. Matt Salmon told leaders of the four pan-democratic parties, [[Democratic Party (Hong Kong)|Democratic Party]] chairwoman [[Emily Lau Wai-hing]], [[Civic Party]] leader [[Alan Leong Kah-kit]], [[Labour Party (Hong Kong)|Labour Party]] chairman [[Lee Cheuk-yan]] and [[Association for Democracy and People's Livelihood]] lawmaker [[Frederick Fung Kin-kee]], that a system where \"people are elected by the people\" was better than one in which leaders were chosen via a narrow constituency, saying that 'sometimes half a loaf is better than no loaf'. Lee said the congressmen had described the proposed chief executive election plan as \"definitely not equal suffrage\" and said they were not trying to convince the pan-democrats but to learn more about the reform debate. Fung said the congressmen had described the reform plan as not fully democratic but had stressed it was a decision for Hongkongers to make. [[Tam Yiu-chung]], ex-chairman of the [[Democratic Alliance for the Betterment and Progress of Hong Kong]] who also met the trio, read the congressmen's interest in compromise as a signal that they wanted to see the reform package passed.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/politics/article/1789329/us-congressmen-probe-hong-kong-politicians-compromise-2017?page=all|title=Visiting US congressmen nudge Hong Kong lawmakers towards compromise on electoral reform|work=South China Morning Post|date=8 May 2015|first1=Jeffie|last1=Lam|first2=Gary|last2=Cheung}}</ref>\n\n===United Kingdom===\nIn July 2014, Anson Chan and Martin Lee visited the United Kingdom and met with [[Deputy Prime Minister]] and the leader of the coalition's junior partner the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] [[Nick Clegg]] and raised concerns over China's jurisdiction of the region, and questioning Britain's commitment to Hong Kong's democratic development. Clegg affirmed Britain's commitment to honour the pledge that if China breached the [[Sino-British Joint Declaration]], Britain would \"mobilize the international community and pursue every legal and other avenue available\".<ref name=\"responsibilities\">{{cite news|url=http://sinosphere.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/07/17/britain-urged-to-live-up-to-responsibilities-in-hong-kong/|newspaper=The New York Times|title=Britain Urged to Live Up to Responsibilities in Hong Kong|first=Alan|last=Wong|date=17 July 2014}}</ref> Clegg also criticised British Prime Minister [[David Cameron]] for prioritising trade with the world's second largest economy over democracy in Hong Kong. A source close to Clegg said Cameron's [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] had become \"so deferential in their attitude to China\" they would not stand up for democracy in Hong Kong. China issued a formal complaint to Britain after the meeting. Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman [[Hong Lei (diplomat)|Hong Lei]] said China was firmly opposed to any foreign interference in its internal affairs on any pretext.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2014/07/16/uk-china-hongkong-britain-idUKKBN0FL1D620140716|title=China protests to Britain after deputy PM meets Hong Kong activists|agency=Reuters|date=16 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nAnson Chan and Martin Lee also attended a [[Foreign Affairs Select Committee]] hearing, speaking out that they were \"concerned that neither of the two signatories to the Joint Declaration \u2013 that is, China and Britain \u2013 is adequately fulfilling their respective responsibilities on the terms of this internationally binding treaty.\" [[Richard Ottaway]], a member of Parliament and chairman of the Foreign Affairs Committee, said that the committee would announce a report as early as next week on the British government's policy toward Hong Kong, but \"it's not a report into the internal operations of Hong Kong.\" Within two months of its publication, the British government will have to respond to the conclusions and recommendations set out in the report.<ref name=\"responsibilities\"/>\n\n[[Liu Xiaoming]], PRC's ambassador to Britain, described Martin Lee and Anson Chan as \"bent on undermining the stability of Hong Kong\". He sent a letter to the members of parliament on 14 July, warned members against visiting Hong Kong. \"I do not think your planned visit to Hong Kong is helpful and strongly advise you not make it,\" Liu wrote. A second letter, from the National People's Congress Foreign Affairs Committee, sent to the British committee in July, saying that the inquiry into post-handover Hong Kong by the committee would be seen as interference in China's internal affairs and called for it to be cancelled.<ref name=\"probe\">{{cite news|title=Britain will 'keep an open mind' in probe of Hong Kong political reform|date=5 September 2014|first=Alice|last=Woodhouse|newspaper=South China Morning Post|url=http://www.scmp.com/news/hong-kong/article/1585839/british-lawmakers-release-angry-letters-china-demanding-end-hong-kong}}</ref> Undeterred by warnings from Beijing, Richard Ottaway told the ''[[Sunday Morning Post]]'': \"We are planning to come in December and I have no reason to think that we won't be there.\" \"The Hong Kong government, the Chinese government and the National People's Congress shouldn't necessarily think that we are automatically hostile,\" Ottaway said.<ref name=\"probe\"/>\n\n[[Chris Patten]], the last [[Governor of Hong Kong]] under the British rule, wrote in the ''[[Financial Times]]'' in September, questioning Britain's \"sense of honour\" in failing to condemn China's planned reforms in Hong Kong, which he said would introduce the kind of stage-managed democracy seen in Iran.<ref>{{cite news|date=2 September 2014|title=Patten criticises UK over failure to act on Hong Kong reforms|first1=George|last1=Parker|first2=Demetri|last2=Sevastopulo|newspaper=Financial Times|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/28b917a8-329b-11e4-a5a2-00144feabdc0.html}}</ref> He said that the UK had a \u201cmoral and political obligation\u201d to defend full democracy in the city.<ref name=\"insult\"/> In response to the remarks by Chris Patten, a spokesman for the [[Leung Chun-ying]]'s Chief Executive's Office on Thursday responded by saying that all Governors of Hong Kong were not elected by Hong Kong people under the British rule; the Sino-British Joint Declaration does not provide for universal suffrage; Hong Kong's constitutional development under the Basic Law is an internal affair of China.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinadailyasia.com/hknews/2014-09/04/content_15163157.html|title=HK CE Office responds to Chris Patten's remarks|work=China Daily|date=4 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the British government's first official response to China's 31 August decision, they said they \"welcome the confirmation that China's objective is for the election of Hong Kong's chief executive through universal suffrage.\" Anson Chan and Martin Lee heavily criticised the UK government's acceptance of China's plan for limiting free elections in its former colony of Hong Kong.<ref name=\"insult\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-09-05/u-k-acceptance-of-hong-kong-election-limits-insult-chan-says.html|title=U.K. Accepting Hong Kong Election Limits 'Insult,' Chan Says|first1=Ting|last1=Shi|first2=Jasmin|last2= Wang|date=5 September 2014|work=Bloomberg}}</ref>\n\nAfter the electoral reform proposal was voted down, British minister [[Hugo Swire]] expressed his country's disappointment at the outcome, and said that \"a transition to universal suffrage is the best way to guarantee Hong Kong\u2019s stability\".<ref>{{cite web|title=UK Response|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/uk-response-to-hong-kong-vote-on-electoral-reform|website=GOV.UK}}</ref>\n\n==Opinion polling==\n\nOn the question (or variants thereof):  \"The National People's Congress Standing Committee has set a framework to limit the number of candidates to two or three and require them to have the support of at least half of the 1,200 nominating committee members. Should the Legislative Council pass or veto the government proposal on the election of the chief executive by universal suffrage based on this framework?\"<ref name=\"opinionpoll\">{{cite news|url=http://hkupop.hku.hk/english/report/scmpPolReform2014/index.html|title=South China Morning Post sponsored 'Survey on Political Reform'|date=11 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: center; line-height: 14px; font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width: 100px;\" ! | Date(s)<br />conducted !! style=\"width: 300px;\" |Polling organisation/client!! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width: 65px;\" | Sample size!! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"background: rgb(0, 129, 66); width: 100px; color: white;\" | Pass!! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"background: rgb(220, 36, 31); width: 100px; color: white;\" |Veto!! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"background: gray; width: 90px; color: white;\" | Undecided!! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width: 80px;\" | Lead\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2015-6-15\" | 11\u201315 Jun || [http://cablenews.i-cable.com/webapps/news_video/index.php?news_id=460204 CSG/Cable TV]|| 1,005 || style=\"background: rgb(153, 255, 153);\" | '''44%''' || 38% || 18% || style=\"background: rgb(0, 129, 66); color: white;\" | 6% \n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2015-6-12\" | 8\u201312 Jun || [http://hkupop.hku.hk/english/features/jointUrollingSurvey/ CUHK CCPOS/HKU POP/HKPU CSPS]|| 1,123 || style=\"background: rgb(153, 255, 153);\" | '''45%''' || 41% || 14% || style=\"background: rgb(0, 129, 66); color: white;\" | 4% \n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2015-6-9\" | 5\u20139 Jun || [http://hkupop.hku.hk/english/features/jointUrollingSurvey/ CUHK CCPOS/HKU POP/HKPU CSPS]|| 1,117 || 41% || style=\"background: rgb(248, 193, 190);\" | '''44%''' || 15% || style=\"background: rgb(220, 36, 31); color: white;\" | 3% \n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2015-6-6\" | 2\u20136 Jun || [http://hkupop.hku.hk/english/features/jointUrollingSurvey/ CUHK CCPOS/HKU POP/HKPU CSPS]|| 1,118 || '''43%''' || '''43%''' || 15% || '''Tied'''\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"2015-6-5\" | 31 May\u20135 Jun || [http: